            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Expected Lifespan: 10-15 years for string inverters, 20-25 years for microinverters\n\nInverters are the only solar component likely requiring replacement during typical system ownership. String inverters (central inverters) contain more complex electronics and capacitors that degrade over time, typically requiring replacement once around year 12-15. Microinverters (Enphase) are more robust with solid-state electronics and typically last 20-25 years matching panel lifespans—one reason we recommend microinverters for most Oro Valley installations.\n\nString Inverter Replacement Costs and Planning: When your string inverter eventually fails (typically showing fault codes, shutting down, or producing reduced power), replacement costs range from $2,000-$4,000 for residential systems depending on size. However, replacement inverters are often more efficient than original models, potentially increasing system production by 2-4%. Many homeowners factor this replacement into their solar economics, planning to replace the inverter once around year 12-15. With proper planning and solar savings, your system will have saved $18,000-$30,000 by year 12, making a $3,000 inverter replacement a minor cost.\n\nMicroinverter Advantages for Long-Term Reliability: Enphase microinverters come with 25-year warranties (matching panel warranties) and typically outlast string inverters. If one microinverter fails, it affects only that single panel while the rest of the system continues producing normally. Replacement microinverters cost $150-$250 each plus service call (compare to $2,000-$4,000 string inverter replacement). Over 25 years, you might replace 2-3 microinverters ($400-$750 total) versus one guaranteed string inverter replacement ($2,000-$4,000)—significant savings plus better reliability."
